  "prompt": "What are the best documentary websites?",
  "response": "The \"best\" documentary website really depends on your taste and what you're looking for. Some focus on free content, while others offer a curated selection with a subscription. Here's a breakdown of some of the top options, categorized for easier browsing:\n\n**Subscription-Based (Paid):**\n\n*   **Criterion Channel:** This is a top pick for cinephiles.  They have a great selection of classic and contemporary documentaries, often focusing on art, film history, and social issues. Known for its high-quality curation and excellent streaming quality.\n*   **MUBI:** Similar to Criterion, MUBI curates a small, rotating selection of films, including documentaries, with a focus on international, independent, and classic cinema. Good for discovering something new and challenging.\n*   **Netflix:** A broad selection of documentaries across almost every topic imaginable. From true crime to nature to celebrity profiles, Netflix offers something for everyone. Quality can vary widely.  It's a good starting point for exploring different genres.\n*   **Hulu:** Similar to Netflix in its breadth. Offers a wide variety of documentaries, often including exclusives and collaborations with other networks. A good complement to Netflix.\n*   **HBO Max:**  Features documentaries from HBO's acclaimed documentary films division, along with content from other sources. Known for high-quality, often investigative, documentary filmmaking.\n*   **Discovery+:**  Focuses on reality, nature, and science documentaries from the Discovery family of networks (Discovery Channel, Animal Planet, TLC, etc.).  A good option if you enjoy these genres.\n*   **Apple TV+:** Growing library with some high-quality documentaries, often with a focus on nature, science, and social issues. Worth checking out for exclusives.\n*   **Curiosity Stream:** Entirely dedicated to documentaries, covering science, history, nature, technology, and society.  A very affordable option if you enjoy educational documentaries.\n\n**Free (Ad-Supported or Crowdfunded):**\n\n*   **YouTube:** A massive platform with countless documentaries, both amateur and professional.  Finding quality can be challenging, but there are excellent channels dedicated to curation (e.g., Real Stories, Free Documentary). Use the search filters to find longer videos/films.\n*   **Internet Archive:** A digital library with a vast collection of films, including many historical documentaries and public domain content. Can be a bit overwhelming to navigate, but a treasure trove of information.\n*   **PBS (and PBS Documentaries YouTube Channel):** PBS has a long history of producing high-quality documentaries, often focused on history, science, and social issues.  Many are available for free on their website or YouTube channel.\n*   **Kanopy:**  Available through many public libraries and universities. Offers a curated selection of films, including documentaries, often focusing on independent and educational titles.\n*   **Vimeo:** Similar to YouTube, but often favored by independent filmmakers.  You can find some excellent, niche documentaries here.\n\n**Niche/Specialized:**\n\n*   **DocAlliance Films:** Focuses on European independent documentary films.\n*   **DAFilms.com:** Also focused on independent documentaries. It often has a curated selection of films, along with reviews and interviews.\n\n**Tips for Finding Good Documentaries Online:**\n\n*   **Read reviews:** Sites like Rotten Tomatoes, IMDb, and Metacritic can help you gauge the quality of a documentary.\n*   **Check for awards:** Award-winning documentaries are often a good bet.\n*   **Look for reputable filmmakers:** Some directors are known for their high-quality work.\n*   **Explore curated lists:** Many websites and blogs compile lists of the best documentaries in specific genres or from specific years.\n*   **Use keywords effectively:** Be specific when searching for documentaries on YouTube or other platforms.  Instead of \"documentary,\" try \"wildlife documentary,\" \"true crime documentary,\" or \"historical documentary.\"\n\n**Ultimately, the best documentary website for you will depend on your individual preferences. I recommend exploring a few of the options listed above to see which ones best suit your needs.**\n",
